        "text": "Still a masterpiece, but revealed in fresh detail in UHD, Henri-Georges Clouzot’s film belongs a hard drivin’ sub-genre in itself; Stephen King praised William Friedkin’s 1977 remake Sorcerer for its intense close-ups of malfunctioning machinery, and The Wages of Fear has been regularly reworked, with The Ice Road a recent example and a Netflix remake due next month (March 2024). But this adaptation of Georges Arnaud’s 1950 French novel Le Salaire de la peur is one of the first truly immersive modern movies; the location shooting is remarkable, the sense of a universally understandable story of life on the edge is fresh and genuine, and the downbeat tone modern and prescient. It’s four men, two trucks, and enough fragile explosives to blow everyone to smithereens; a perfect suspense movie done right.\n\nYou probably already know the story; here’s the one liner. In Latin American village, four disparate, desperate men led by Yves Montand are hired by an oil company to transport a lethal cargo of nitroglycerine to a massive oil-well fire. That fire looks like an alien landscape, and the high-definition picks out visuals you won’t have seen before; the way the constant explosions seem to expand and contact before your eyes, driving the men to distraction and death. The oil they sink into is inky black, poisoning drivers who are ‘drunk on nitro’ and just about ready to combust. In this hell, headlamps look like devil’s eyes, sweat pours like rivulets, while dirty fingers wipe the grime off speedometers and rotten wood gives way beneath the slowly moving rubber tyres of the cargo trucks.\n\nThe Wages of Fear is very much about how the poor are abused and destroyed by the rich; it’s timeless in its simplicity and the polemic hits hard. There’s supposedly no smoking within 50 feet of the trucks, but in the stressful circumstances, everyone puffs like factory chimneys; they’re men on the edge of a collective, shared insanity. ‘Your lungs are full of cement,’ a doctor says disapprovingly, but an appetite for self-destruction is a condition of the job, something goes with the territory. Whether inching forward on collapsing platforms, navigating boulders in the road or flying over bumps at 40mph, it’s just one impossible obstacle after another, and even a safe arrival doesn’t mean that you’re safe; death is always waiting; The Wages of Fear is an elevated action movie that suddenly becomes dark poetry to watch.\n\nThis BFI blu-ray UHD release reveals more than ever of Clouzot’s vision; the murals on the walls of the village, the insects alighting on the tables, the dirt, the sweat, the tears. ‘You’ll vibrate, man!’ says one character; this venerable, classic, timeless movie has been artfully revived in a way that should have you vibrating all the way to South America and back, over 500km of bad road.\n\nhttps://shop.bfi.org.uk/the-wages-of-fear-4k-ultra-hd.html\n\nReleased on UHD Blu-ray, iTunes and Amazon Prime on 19 February 2024\n\nThanks to the BFI for blu-ray UHD access. Special features include…\n\n4K (2160p) UHD Blu-ray presentation in Dolby Vision (HDR10 compatible)\n\nA Road Trip Out of Hell? Or Into It? – Purgatory and The Wages of Fear (2023, 15 mins): a new video essay by filmmaker and photographer Nic Wassell – NEW for this release\n\nAudio commentary with film critic Adrian Martin\n\nInterview with Professor Lucy Mazdon (2017, 35 mins): an in-depth discussion on Henri-Georges Clouzot and The Wages of Fear\n\nInterview with assistant director Michel Romanoff (2009, 23 mins)\n\nInterview with Clouzot biographer Marc Godin (2009, 10 mins)\n\nThe Guardian Lecture: Yves Montand (100 mins, audio only): in conversation with Don Allen; the star of The Wages of Fear discusses his distinguished career\n\nTreasures from the BFI National Archive (1920-1960, 30 mins): a selection of archive gems, exploring some of the themes and iconography featured in The Wages of Fear – NEW for this release\n\nOriginal theatrical trailer\n\n***First pressing only*** Illustrated booklet with an essay by Andy Miller, original reviews from Sight & Sound and Monthly Film Bulletin, an appreciation of Clouzot by Paul Ryan, notes on the special features and credits\n\nProduct details"
